  "text": "The structure of microbial communities was assessed by automated ribosomal intergenic spacer analysis (ARISA). DNA was extracted from frozen (À80°C) sediment following [CITATION_1] . The extraction involved mechanical cell breakage, enzymatic digestion of unwanted cell constituents, and DNA purification. The purified DNA was stored at À20°C. PCR amplification of the intergenic region of bacterial rDNA was carried out using labelled forward primer 1406F-FAM (5′FAM-TGY ACA CAC CGC CCG T-3′, T=T, C) and reverse primer 23Sr (5′-GGG TTB CCC CAT TCR G-3′, B=G, T, C and R=G, A; Microsynth, Balgach, Switzerland; [CITATION_2] . Although designed to amplify bacterial rDNA, these primers can also bind to chloroplast and mitochondrial DNA, such that the resulting community fingerprints could include algae as well as other eukaryotes. Therefore, we refer to microbial community structure when interpreting ARISA profiles. The mix contained 1 9 GoTaq â Flexi reaction buffer, 3 mM MgCl 2 , 0.25 mM dNTPs, 0.4 mM of each primer, 0.25 mg mL À1 bovine serum albumin (BSA), 0.05 U lL",
